{"title": "Bury Your Disabled", "content": "Bury Your Disabled happens when a disabled character is killed off in a movie or TV Show. There are four types of Bury Your Disabled.\n\u2022 Type 1: Someone who is disabled and dies at the end of the movie due to natural causes. Usually due to complications arising from their disability (Rory O'Shea Was Here). Depending on the nature of the disability, may be Truth in Television.\n\u2022 Type 2: This type occurs when the disabled person is killed off in a violent manner. This can be because they (the disabled character) were considered, by the writer and audience, an easier victim because of their disability. Type 2 tends to carry the Unfortunate Implication that someone who is disabled can't protect themselves. This can be Truth in Television , but that depends on the specific disability \u0097 and even the crippling ones can be compensated for these days. Before the 20th century... not so much. Type 2 usually involves murder or neglect.\n\u2022 Type 3: Suicide, which carries the Unfortunate Implication that one is better off dead than disabled. Or, worst case scenario, the writer who uses this trope really does believe that one is better dead than disabled.\n\u2022 Type 4: Mercy kill. Someone close to the disabled kills \u0097 or even murders \u0097 the disabled, either by his/her request or thinking that life as a disabled person would be too hard to bear. This type overlaps outright murder, Mercy Kill, and euthanasia, and carries the same Unfortunate Implications as Type 3.\n\nMore than likely the character in question is being killed off by the writers specifically because he/she is disabled. This is usually a plot point that is supposed to be a Tear Jerker or, in the case of horror movies, meant to be shocking. This can also combine with Littlest Cancer Patient: the frail, wheelchair-bound waif is Too Good for This Sinful Earth, and their death will be a sweet release at the end.\n\nBury Your Disabled will most likely happen to a current or (near-)future wheelchair user, but other disabilities are not discriminated against as much. See also Death by Disfigurement, which has some similar implications, I Will Only Slow You Down, where a disabled person volunteers to be left behind, and Throwing Off the Disability, the other common way to \"dispose of\" a disabled character. Compare to Bullying the Disabled, which can also lead to this, and Abandon the Disabled.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/BuryYourDisabled", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/RoryOSheaWasHere", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/ASilentVoice", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/AttackOnTitan", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Fray", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/BuffyTheVampireSlayer", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/JossWhedon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Felidae", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/AlphaAndOmega", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/RoryOSheaWasHere", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/FullMetalJacket", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheTexasChainSawMassacre1974", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/PsychoBeachParty", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/BreakfastOnPluto", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/FinalDestination1", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/HellraiserHellworld", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Gattaca", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/StevenSeagal", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/OutForJustice", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/BladeTrinity", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/BarbWire", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/FridayThe13thPart2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/ANightmareOnElmStreet", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/ANightmareOnElmStreet3DreamWarriors", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/FreddysDeadTheFinalNightmare", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheCurseOfFrankenstein", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheRelic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/OneFlewOverTheCuckoosNest", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/MillionDollarBaby", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/SchindlersList", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/PowerRangers2017", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/DragonQueen", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/Animorphs", "/pmwiki/pmwi